of warfare: why and how people are motivated to fight, and how they behave once they do fight. Yet the specific Canadian context, experience, and perspective are often lost in favour of appeals to universal truths. The first major Canadian study of combat motivation in almost forty years, Why We Fight redresses this imbalance by presenting some of the best new work on the subject. Bringing together top military practitioners and scholars to discuss some of the most controversial issues of modern warfare, Why We Fight examines the face of battle as experienced by Canadians. It explores sexual violence in war, professionalism, organizations, leadership, shared intent, motivation in extremis, and the toxicity of the "warrior" culture. Its chapters offer key insights on combat motivation theories, the modern operating environment, and the collective and individual identities of the men and women who fight for Canada. Many worry that technology is leading us towards a post-human age, particularly in war. Why We Fight affirms the centrality of the human being in warfare in Canada's past, present, and future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCombatxPsychological aspects. 0aMilitary art and sciencezCanada. 0aMilitary educationzCanada. 0aMilitary moralezCanada. 0aMotivation (Psychology). 0aPsychology, Military. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh1 aBreede, H. Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBreede, H. Christian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aClark, Joshua, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCookson-Hills, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Karen D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDussault, Sonia, econtributor.4ctb